Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: AccessKenya, Safaricom, Stanbic

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-09-13T15:28:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-13/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-accesskenya-united-bank-for-africa.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for
the first day in three, jumping 1.5 percent to 61.12 by the 3
p.m. end of trading in Nairobi, the biggest gain since March 15.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index slipped for a
fourth day, losing 0.2 percent to 1,114.22 by the 3 p.m. close
in Accra, the lowest level since April 29. Mauritius’s SEMDEX
Index fell for a third day, sliding 0.2 percent to 1,925.58 by
the 1:30 p.m. end of trading in  Port Louis , the lowest close
since Aug. 22. The FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  snapped two days
of declines, rising 1.1 percent to 774.74 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index retreated
less than 0.1 percent to 21,018.52 by the 2:30 p.m. close in
Lagos, according to a statement on the exchange’s website, a
fourth day of decreases.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  AccessKenya (ACCESS)  Group Ltd. (ACCESS KN), the East African
nation’s only publicly traded Internet company, rose 15 cents,
or 2.7 percent, to 5.75 shillings, the highest close since Sept.
5, on bets its decline this year is overdone. The stock’s 14-day
relative strength index has been below 30, the level that
signals to some technical analysts a security is poised to
increase, since Aug. 15, closing at 27.6 yesterday.  Safaricom Ltd. (SAFCOM)  ,  East Africa ’s biggest mobile-
phone company, rose for the first time in three days, increasing
10 cents, or 3.3 percent, to 3.10 shillings. Kenyan mobile-
telephone operators are expected to raise calling rates for
customers on the back of a weak shilling and high inflation,
Bitange Ndemo, permanent secretary in the ministry of
information and communications told Reuters in an interview in
Nairobi yesterday.  Stanbic IBTC Bank Plc (IBTCCB)  , a Nigerian unit of
Standard Bank Group Ltd., climbed 25 kobo, or 2.7 percent, to
9.5 naira, the highest since Sept. 9. The lender said it expects
to report net income of 2.77 billion naira ($17.9 million) for
the fourth quarter.  United Bank for Africa Plc (UBA)  , a Nigerian lender with
operations in 18 countries, climbed for the first day in seven,
advancing 12 kobo, or 3.1 percent, to 4 naira, the biggest
closing gain since Aug. 25. The Lagos-based bank forecast profit
after tax of 14.5 billion naira for the fourth quarter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
